SIMPLE: pithy
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pithy
<hw>Pith"y</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos>
<adjf>Pithier</adjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Pithiest</adjf>.]</amorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Consisting wholly, or
in part, of pith; abounding in pith; <as>as, a <ex>pithy</ex> stem; a
<ex>pithy</ex> fruit.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Having nervous energy; forceful; cogent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>pithy</qex> speech prevailed, and all agreed.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In all these Goodman Fact was very short, but
<qex>pithy</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Pithy gall</b></col> <fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>a large,
rough, furrowed, oblong gall, formed on blackberry canes by a small
gallfly (<spn>Diastrophus nebulosus</spn>).</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1092 --></p>

<p><ent>Pitiable</ent>⟦br⟧
